<TITLE> Stocks close down after last week's gains </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Mar 02 (bdnews24.com)  The country's bourses closed slightly down Sunday after last week's gains, mainly due to investors' sell-offs to lock in profits. Turnover and trading volume also witnessed declines from the last trading day. Market observers cited the fall as a natural phenomenon saying it was anticipated the market would see investors selling off holdings for profit taking. "The indices went up during the last week. A fall in indices was anticipated on the opening day as investors sell off to gain profits," DSE chief executive Salahuddin Ahmed said. Trading was halted on the Dhaka Stock exchange due to technical reasons at about 12.53 pm, resuming again at around 5.30 pm for half an hour to wrap up the day's trades. Dhaka stocks kicked-off the day on a positive note in the general index but started to fall after the second hour. The market remained steady however towards its halt at 12..53 pm, and remained flat during the last half hour after trading resumed to finish downbeat. The benchmark DGEN or general index declined 17.54 points or 0.59 percent to end on 2913.84 while the DSI or all share price index finished at 2463.84, down 12.52 points or 0.50 percent. The DSE-20 blue chip however, gained 10.43 points or 0.45 percent, to close at 2328.75. Turnover on the country's prime bourse fell to Tk 1.83 billion from Thursday's Tk 1.99 billion, from 8,091,869 traded shares. Of the issues traded, 116 advanced, 99 declined and ten remained unchanged. Banks, pharmaceuticals, oil companies and mutual funds drove the day's trading. Mutual funds and pharmaceuticals gained Sunday with banks ending mixed while oil issues fell. AB Bank closed 1.72 percent down to Tk 3114.75. Pharmaceuticals leader Square Pharma ended 4.21 percent up at Tk 3529.75. Grameen One Mutual Fund rose 1.91 percent to Tk 122.20. IFIC Bank fell 1.33 percent to end on Tk 2861.75. ACI rose 4.35 percent to Tk 189.30. Among other scrips on the turnover board--Jamuna Oil, Meghna Petroleum, NBL fell, while Dutch Bangla Bank and UCBL gained. All the sectors on the Chittagong Stock Exchange closed mixed with indices closing lower. Ceramics, pharmaceuticals and mutual funds advanced the most while energy, ICT and miscellaneous saw the largest losses. The CSCX or selective categories index fell 23.21 points, or 0.48 percent, to 4801.56. The CASPI or all share price index finished at 7506.05, down 30.87 points or 0.40 percent. The bourse's blue chip CSE-30 also lost 4.81 points or 0.07 percent, to end on 6737.24. Turnover amounted to Tk 366.75 million from 2,209,842 traded shares. Losers beat gainers 70 to 57 while eleven issues held steady. bdn
